article.description:
Roger Powell scored a career-high 22 points and Brian Cook added
17 as 16th-ranked Illinois won its 16th straight home game, an
80-54 Big Ten victory over the stumbling Hoosiers.
article.headline: Illini victory puts Hoosiers squarely on bubble
article.linkText: Illinois rips Indiana, clogs crowded Big Ten race
article.story: CHAMPAIGN, Ill. (AP) -- Brian Cook's second-half spark was all Illinois needed to run away to another victory at Assembly Hall. Cook scored nine points in a decisive 25-15 run to open the second half and the Illini (No. 16 ESPN/USA Today, No. 18 AP) beat Indiana 80-54 Tuesday night, the Hoosiers' seventh loss in 10 games. "I just got the ball in good position,'' said Cook, the Big Ten's leading scorer. "I knew I wasn't shooting it that well in the first half, but I knew if I kept on shooting it was going to go in. That's how scorers always think.'' The Illini (19-5, 9-4 Big Ten) won their third straight overall and 16th straight in Assembly Hall as they pulled into a second-place tie with Wisconsin in the conference. Their last three wins in Champaign have been by a total of 75 points. "We're feeling real good here,'' Cook said. "We want to keep this thing rolling. "The guards are playing great. The big guys are playing great. We've just got to take that intensity on the road,'' he said. The Illini play their next two games at conference-leading Michigan and Wisconsin. It doesn't worry Cook. "Things are clicking. We're ready to take this show on the road,'' he said. Indiana coach Mike Davis said his team lost control of the game in the last four minutes of the first half. "We took four or five extremely bad shots,'' he said. "After the first 16 minutes, we didn't play well at all.'' Jeff Newton had 11 points for Indiana (16-10, 6-7). Illinois opened the second half with a 9-2 run that was capped by Dee Brown's 3-pointer with 16:20 remaining. Indiana closed the gap to 10, but Cook made a layup and a 3-pointer and Brown hit from the outside to put Illinois in control for good. "Everybody was aggressive tonight. That's how I want to play. That's how we're supposed to play,'' Illinois coach Bill Self said. Roger Powell scored 22 points for Illinois, his second career high in as many games. He scored 20 in Illinois' 73-61 win over Northwestern last Saturday. "My confidence is pretty high right now,'' Powell said. "That's what you need and that's how it should be when you go into March.'' George Leach and Tom Coverdale each scored nine points for Indiana, which was 8-of-25 from the field in the second half and shot 37 percent for the game. Illinois' defense, ranked second in the Big Ten, had nine steals and forced 10 turnovers. The game was tied three times and the lead changed hands four times before the Illini pulled away with an 8-2 run to close the half. Cook's hook shot from 10 feet made it 39-28 and Indiana's Marshall Strickland scored the final basket of the half. Davis said he's not counting his team out. He said three wins to finish the season would give the Hoosiers 19, the same number they ended the regular season with last year, when they went to the NCAA championship game.
